    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-01-25T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-01-25T05:00:00-05:00" n="884"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d884">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2399: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-01-25T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 25, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 25—9:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>113. 1. In Embassy’s 114, January 25, 8 p.m.<note n="69" xml:id="d884fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> is given substance of instructions received by my British
                        colleague<note n="70" xml:id="d884fn2">Sir Robert L. Craigie, British
                        Ambassador in Japan.</note> in which he is directed to inquire if I am
                    prepared to make parallel representations to the Japanese Government concerning
                    attempted assassination of Chairman of the Shanghai Municipal Council<note
                        n="71" xml:id="d884fn3">W. J. Keswick, British businessman.</note> by
                    Chairman of Japanese Ratepayers Association.<note n="72" xml:id="d884fn4">Y.
                        Hayashi.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0833" n="823" xml:id="pg_823"/>
                <p>2. The British Ambassador has an appointment with the Vice Minister<note n="73"
                        xml:id="d884fn5">Chuichi Ohashi.</note> for the foregoing purpose [Monday?]
                    morning. I already have an appointment with the Foreign Minister<note n="74"
                        xml:id="d884fn6">Yosuke Matsuoka.</note> on Monday morning to take up the
                    Peiping marine gendarme incident of December 30.<note n="75" xml:id="d884fn7"
                        >For Ambassador Grew’s memorandum and oral statement, January 27, 1941, see
                            <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_707">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 707</ref>; see also <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_454">pp. 454</ref>–<ref target="#pg_483"
                            >483</ref>, <hi rend="italic">passim</hi>.</note> If the Department
                    desires to instruct me to broach both cases at the same time, a telegram should
                    be despatched from Washington direct to Tokyo not later than Saturday evening
                    (today).</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
